HEADWORD: Cass
<hw>Cass</hw> <pr>(k⟦acr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>casser</ets>, LL. <ets>cassare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>cassus</ets>
empty, hollow, and perhaps influenced by L. <ets>quassare</ets> to
shake, shatter, v. intens. of <ets>quatere</ets> to shake. Cf.
<er>Cashier</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Quash</er>,
<er>Cask</er>.]</ety> <def>To render useless or void; to quash; to
annul; to reject; to send away.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W.
Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cassada</ent>⟦br⟧
